The article discusses the U.S.-Africa cooperation on trade and investment under the Obama administration. It highlights the economic potential of Africa and the efforts made by African countries to diversify their economies, improve regional and global economic cooperation, and overcome barriers to trade and investment. The United States has committed to being a partner in these efforts through initiatives such as the Doing Business in Africa Campaign, Power Africa, and Trade Africa. The article also mentions the expansion of U.S. government presence and economic engagement in Africa, with various agencies opening new offices and increasing their portfolios on the continent. It emphasizes the financial and technical tools and programs offered by the U.S. government to support U.S. businesses looking to trade with and invest in Africa. The article further discusses the U.S. government's support for the next generation of African leaders and makers, as well as its efforts to combat corruption at home and abroad.